(Monad Mini-PC Small Pruned Node Setup Guide) Tj
0 -12 Td
(===========================================) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(Purpose) Tj
0 -12 Td
(-------) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(This guide explains how to set up a small pruned Monad node similar to the) Tj
0 -12 Td
(mini-PC used for these public reports. It is written for beginners, but it) Tj
0 -12 Td
(keeps enough technical detail to be useful for operators and researchers.) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(This build is not intended to supply large public infrastructure. It is a) Tj
0 -12 Td
(small-scale design for one operator or a small trusted group of roughly 2-3) Tj
0 -12 Td
(people. It is not a full-history archive node and should not be described as) Tj
0 -12 Td
(one. The goal is not to replace professional RPC providers, archive providers,) Tj
0 -12 Td
(or high-capacity validator infrastructure. The goal is to show that many) Tj
0 -12 Td
(well-run local nodes can strengthen the network by handling their own traffic) Tj
0 -12 Td
(and reducing some dependence on larger shared services.) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(Why run a small pruned node?) Tj
0 -12 Td
(----------------------------) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(1. Privacy and security) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(   Sending transactions through your own node reduces the amount of transaction) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   and usage data you expose to third-party RPC providers. You still interact) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   with the public blockchain, but your local workflow does not need to depend) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   on somebody else's public RPC endpoint for every request.) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(2. Low local latency) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(   A local node can give very fast access to chain state and WebSocket data for) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   bots, dashboards, or trading tools running on the same network. For) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   high-volume trading or monitoring, local RPC and WebSocket access can remove) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   the delay and rate limits that often come from public endpoints.) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(3. Network support) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(   This kind of node follows the current chain, executes recent state, serves) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   local RPC requests, and participates in node networking. It is not the same) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   thing as being an active validator unless the node identity is accepted into) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   the validator set, and it does not store full historical archive data. It can) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   still reduce load on larger shared RPC and validator-adjacent infrastructure.) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(4. Practical decentralization) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(   One mini-PC cannot serve the world. Many small nodes, each tuned for a) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   household, small team, or local application stack, make the network more) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   resilient. This is especially useful when those nodes are distributed across) Tj
0 -12 Td
(   different homes, networks, cities, and operators.) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(Important limits) Tj
0 -12 Td
(----------------) Tj
0 -12 Td
() Tj
0 -12 Td
(- This setup is intended for recent chain data, not full-history archival use.) Tj
0 -12 Td
(- In this experiment, historical) Tj
0 -12 Td
(  data older than roughly 20 days should be backfilled from another source.) Tj
0 -12 Td
(- This guide assumes bare-metal Linux, not a cloud VM.) Tj
ET
endstream
